I encourage you to share Ada‚Äôs story. For every Mark, Elon, Bill or Sam there is an Ada, Katherine, Marie and Radia.
In the late seventies, the Department of Defense developed a software language called Ada‚Äîone that brought together a number of different programming languages.

There was a greater backlash and an attempt to reclaim it as a male activity in order to keep that wealth and power in a man‚Äôs hands, to try to redefine it as something a woman didn‚Äôt do, and shouldn‚Äôt do, and couldn‚Äôt do.‚Äù

When the value of what Ada wrote is this paper was understood, historians and scholars would argue that what Ada did write in this paper was greatly overstated and that she was manic depressive and had delusions about her own talent.

have rendered possible. Thus not only the mental and the material, but the theoretical and the practical in the mathematical world, are brought into more intimate and effective connection with each other.‚Äù

She continues ‚ÄúA new, a vast, and a powerful language is developed for the future use of analysis, in which to wield its truths so that these may become of more speedy and accurate practical application for the purposes of mankind than the means hitherto in our possession

‚ÄúThe science of operations, as derived from mathematics more especially, is a science of itself, and has its own abstract truth and value,‚Äù Lovelace wrote, this passage alone is Ada inventing a special term for Computing; The science of operations.

This paper is described as Ada greatest contribution to computer science. She described with clarity how Babbage‚Äôs device would work, illuminating its foundations, the engine weaved algebraic patterns.

They corresponded from 1835 to 1852 when Babbage devised a new invention ‚Äòthe Analytical Machine‚Äô. Ada would serve as key interpreter. She took a draft paper released to describe the machine, added 14,000 words and rewrote it in French, published in 1843.
At the age of 17, she met Charles Babbage, mathematician and widower in his 40s. He told her about his invention ‚Äòthe Different machine‚Äô.
Which is an interesting fact as a girl she technically was ‚Äònot allowed‚Äô to learn mathematics.
Her mother Annabella  Byron was called ‚Äòthe Princess of Parallelograms‚Äô by her father Lord Byron, a poet. It was her mothers request Ada study mathematics, music and French.
When she was 12 she wanted to fly. So she studied birds and wrote her research into a book called Flyology.
